SIMPLE: shaft
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shaft
<hw>Shaft</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>shaft</ets>,
<ets>schaft</ets>, AS. <ets>sceaft</ets>; akin to D. <ets>schacht</ets>,
OHG. <ets>scaft</ets>, G. <ets>schaft</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>skaft</ets>
handle, haft, Icel. <ets>skapt</ets>, and probably to L.
<ets>scapus</ets>, Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/, <?/<?/<?/<?/, a staff. Probably
originally, a shaven or smoothed rod. Cf. <er>Scape</er>,
<er>Scepter</er>, <er>Shave</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The slender,
smooth stem of an arrow; hence, an arrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His sleep, his meat, his drink, is him bereft,⟦br⟧
That lean he wax, and dry as is a <qex>shaft</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>shaft</qex> hath three principal parts, the stele [stale],
the feathers, and the head.</q> <rj><qau>Ascham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The long handle of a spear or similar weapon; hence,
the weapon itself; (<mark>Fig.</mark>) anything regarded as a shaft to
be thrown or darted; <as>as, <ex>shafts</ex> of light</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the thunder,⟦br⟧
Winged with red lightning and impetuous rage,⟦br⟧
Perhaps hath spent his <qex>shafts</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some kinds of literary pursuits . . . have been attacked with all
the <qex>shafts</qex> of ridicule.</q> <rj><qau>V. Knox.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which resembles in some degree the stem or
handle of an arrow or a spear; a long, slender part, especially when
cylindrical.</def> Specifically: (a) <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The trunk,
stem, or stalk of a plant.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>The stem or midrib of a feather.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The pole,
or tongue, of a vehicle; also, a thill.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The part
of a candlestick which supports its branches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt make a candlestick of pure gold . . . his
<qex>shaft</qex>, and his branches, his bowls, his knops, and his
flowers, shall be of the same.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxv. 31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>The handle or helve of certain tools, instruments,
etc., as a hammer, a whip, etc.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>A pole,
especially a Maypole.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Stow.</au>
<sd>(g)</sd> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The body of a column; the
cylindrical pillar between the capital and base (see <xex>Illust.</xex>
of <er>Column</er>). Also, the part of a chimney above the roof. Also,
the spire of a steeple.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark> <au>Gwilt.</au>
<sd>(h)</sd> <def>A column, an obelisk, or other spire-shaped or
columnar monument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bid time and nature gently spare⟦br⟧
The <qex>shaft</qex> we raise to thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(i)</sd> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>A rod at the end of a
heddle.</def> <sd>(j)</sd> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A solid or hollow
cylinder or bar, having one or more journals on which it rests and
revolves, and intended to carry one or more wheels or other revolving
parts and to transmit power or motion; <as>as, the <ex>shaft</ex> of a
steam engine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A humming bird (<spn>Thaumastura
cora</spn>) having two of the tail feathers next to the middle ones very
long in the male; -- called also <altname>cora humming
bird</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>schacht</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A well-like excavation in the earth,
perpendicular or nearly so, made for reaching and raising ore, for
raising water, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A long passage for the admission or outlet of air;
an air shaft.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The chamber of a blast furnace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Line shaft</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a main shaft
of considerable length, in a shop or factory, usually bearing a number
of pulleys by which machines are driven, commonly by means of
countershafts; -- called also <altname>line</altname>, or <altname>main
line</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Shaft alley</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a passage extending from the engine room to the
stern, and containing the propeller shaft.</cd> -- <col><b>Shaft
furnace</b></col> <fld>(Metal.)</fld>, <cd>a furnace, in the form of a
chimney, which is charged at the top and tapped at the
bottom.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shafted</ent>⟦br⟧
